    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my physics midterms and im a bit stuck. can u give me a quick summary of quantum entanglement? specifically i need to understand what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation. keep it simple and try not to use too much math if u can. thanks!",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become linked so that the state of one instantly influences the state of the other, no matter how far apart they are. This is fundamentally different from classical correlation, which only arises because the particles shared specific information at the moment they were created, whereas entangled particles do not have definite properties until they are measured. In a classical system, measuring one object simply reveals a pre-existing value, while in quantum entanglement, the act of measurement forces the distant particle into a corresponding state, defying our intuition about local reality. This \"spooky action at a distance\" has been confirmed by experiments testing Bell's inequalities, proving that nature is not simply like a pair of gloves in boxes.",
